baptism. Anlezark studies a range of texts against their historical background, and discusses shifting emphases in the way the Flood was interpreted for diverse audiences. The book concludes with a discussion of Beowulf, relating the epic poem’s presentation of the Flood myth to that of other Anglo-Saxon texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChristian literature, English (Old)xHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity and literaturezEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aDeluge in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aFloods in literature. 0aFloodsxMythologyzEngland. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAndreas.  aAnglo-Saxons.  aBede.  aBeowulf.  aChristianity.  aExodus.  aFlood myth.  aNoah.  aapocalypse.  abiblical story.  acovenant.  acultural self-definition.  ahistorical metaphor.  ainheritance.  amysticism.  asin and punishment.  avital myth.1 aAnlezark, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129659/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013